## USER RESEARCH

### Audience Intent on the Page
This reader has already decided they want almond nails. They are not browsing — they are here to execute. Their core need is a reliable, beginner-safe method that produces consistent results across all ten nails. They fear asymmetry above all else. Many have tried and failed once already. Secondary need: reassurance that their current nail length is workable, or guidance on what to do if it is not. They want to leave this page ready to pick up a file.

### Top 5 Pain Points
1. **Asymmetry across nails** — one nail always ends up a different shape or length than the others; readers report discovering this only after painting.
2. **Filing too much off one side** — sawing back and forth or over-filing one edge leaves nails thin, weak, and lopsided.
3. **Nails too short for almond** — readers unsure whether their current nail length is enough; frustration when the shape collapses to oval or round.
4. **Tip ends up too sharp or too flat** — either accidentally mimicking stiletto (too pointed) or just a blunt oval (too flat); can't find the middle ground.
5. **Nails breaking during or after shaping** — weak or brittle nails splitting at the filed tip; especially common for those who have had gel/acrylic damage or who used a coarse file.

### User Sentiment
Aspirational but anxious — readers want the salon look at home but are intimidated by the precision required; tone should reassure and empower without condescension.

